<doc id="41248" wikidata="Q5955593" url="?curid=41248" title="Hydroxyl ion absorption">
<text>Hydroxyl ion absorption is the absorption in optical fibers of electromagnetic radiation, including the near-infrared, due to the presence of trapped hydroxyl ions remaining from water as a contaminant. 

The hydroxyl (OH−) ion can penetrate glass during or after product fabrication, resulting in significant attenuation of discrete optical wavelengths, &quot;e.g.&quot;, centred at 1.383 μm, used for communications via optical fibres.

==See also==
* Electromagnetic absorption by water

